# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: voltage-references
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:voltage-references/shunt-regulator] A **voltage regulator** is a system designed to automatically maintain a constant voltage.
[src:voltage-references/shunt-regulator] It may use a simple feed-forward design or may include negative feedback.
[src:voltage-references/shunt-regulator] It may use an electromechanical mechanism or electronic components.
[src:voltage-references/shunt-regulator] Depending on the design, it may be used to regulate one or more AC or DC voltages.
[src:voltage-references/shunt-regulator] Electronic voltage regulators are found in devices such as computer power supplies, where they stabilize the DC voltages used by the processor and other elements.
[src:voltage-references/shunt-regulator] In automobile alternators and central power station generator plants, voltage regulators control the output of the plant.
[src:voltage-references/shunt-regulator] In an electric power distribution system, voltage regulators may be installed at a substation or along distribution lines so that all customers receive steady voltage independent of how much power is drawn from the line.
[src:voltage-references/shunt-regulator] A simple voltage regulator can be made from a resistor in series with a forward-biased diode (or series of diodes), forming a voltage divider of sorts.
[src:voltage-references/shunt-regulator] Due to the logarithmic shape of diode V-I curves, the voltage across the diode changes only slightly due to changes in current drawn or changes in the input.
[src:voltage-references/shunt-regulator] When precise voltage control and efficiency are not important, this design may be adequate.
[src:voltage-references/shunt-regulator] Since the forward voltage of a diode is small, this kind of voltage regulator is only suitable for low-voltage regulated output.
[src:voltage-references/shunt-regulator] When higher-voltage output is needed, a reverse-biased zener diode or a series of zener diodes may be employed.
[src:voltage-references/shunt-regulator] Zener diode regulators make use of the zener diode's fixed reverse voltage, which can be quite large.
[src:voltage-references/shunt-regulator] Feedback voltage regulators operate by comparing the actual output voltage to some fixed reference voltage.
[src:voltage-references/shunt-regulator] Any difference is amplified and used to control the regulation element in such a way as to reduce the voltage error.
[src:voltage-references/shunt-regulator] This forms a negative feedback control loop; increasing the open-loop gain tends to increase regulation accuracy but reduce stability.
[src:voltage-references/shunt-regulator] Stability is the avoidance of oscillation, or ringing, during step changes in load or input voltage.
[src:voltage-references/shunt-regulator] There will also be a trade-off between stability and the speed of the response to changes.
[src:voltage-references/shunt-regulator] However, many regulators have over-current protection, so that they will entirely stop sourcing current (or limit the current in some way) if the output current is too high, and some regulators may also shut down if the input voltage is outside a given range (see also: Crowbar (circuit)).
[src:voltage-references/shunt-regulator] In electromechanical regulators, voltage regulation is easily accomplished by coiling the sensing wire to make an electromagnet.
[src:voltage-references/shunt-regulator] The magnetic field produced by the current attracts a moving ferrous core held back under spring tension or gravitational pull.
[src:voltage-references/shunt-regulator] As voltage increases, so does the current, strengthening the magnetic field produced by the coil and pulling the core towards the field.
[src:voltage-references/shunt-regulator] The magnet is physically connected to a mechanical power switch, which opens as the magnet moves into the field.
[src:voltage-references/shunt-regulator] As voltage decreases, so does the current, releasing spring tension or the weight of the core and causing it to retract.
[src:voltage-references/shunt-regulator] This closes the switch and allows the power to flow once more.
[src:voltage-references/shunt-regulator] The relay(s) modulated the width of a current pulse to regulate the voltage output of the generator by controlling the average field current in the rotating machine which determines strength of the magnetic field produced which determines the unloaded output voltage per rpm.
[src:voltage-references/shunt-regulator] Capacitors are not used to smooth the pulsed voltage as described earlier.
[src:voltage-references/shunt-regulator] The large inductance of the field coil stores the energy delivered to the magnetic field in an iron core so the pulsed field current does not result in as strongly pulsed a field.
[src:voltage-references/shunt-regulator] Both types of rotating machine produce a rotating magnetic field that induces an alternating current in the coils in the stator.
[src:voltage-references/shunt-regulator] A generator uses a mechanical commutator, graphite brushes running on copper segments, to convert the AC produced into DC by switching the external connections at the shaft angle when the voltage would reverse.
[src:voltage-references/shunt-regulator] An alternator accomplishes the same goal using rectifiers that do not wear down and require replacement.
[src:voltage-references/shunt-regulator] Modern designs now use *solid state* technology (transistors) to perform the same function that the relays perform in electromechanical regulators.
[src:voltage-references/shunt-regulator] Electromechanical regulators are used for mains voltage stabilisation—see AC voltage stabilizers below.
[src:voltage-references/shunt-regulator] Generators, as used in power stations, ship electrical power production, or standby power systems, will have automatic voltage regulators (AVR) to stabilize their voltages as the load on the generators changes.
[src:voltage-references/shunt-regulator] The first AVRs for generators were electromechanical systems, but a modern AVR uses solid-state devices.
[src:voltage-references/shunt-regulator] An AVR is a feedback control system that measures the output voltage of the generator, compares that output to a set point, and generates an error signal that is used to adjust the excitation of the generator.
[src:voltage-references/shunt-regulator] As the excitation current in the field winding of the generator increases, its terminal voltage will increase.
[src:voltage-references/shunt-regulator] The AVR will control current by using power electronic devices; generally a small part of the generator's output is used to provide current for the field winding.
[src:voltage-references/shunt-regulator] Where a generator is connected in parallel with other sources such as an electrical transmission grid, changing the excitation has more of an effect on the reactive power produced by the generator than on its terminal voltage, which is mostly set by the connected power system.
[src:voltage-references/shunt-regulator] Where multiple generators are connected in parallel, the AVR system will have circuits to ensure all generators operate at the same power factor.
[src:voltage-references/shunt-regulator] AVRs on grid-connected power station generators may have additional control features to help stabilize the electrical grid against upsets due to sudden load loss or faults.
[src:voltage-references/shunt-regulator] This is an older type of regulator used in the 1920s that uses the principle of a fixed-position field coil and a second field coil that can be rotated on an axis in parallel with the fixed coil, similar to a variocoupler.
[src:voltage-references/shunt-regulator] When the movable coil is positioned perpendicular to the fixed coil, the magnetic forces acting on the movable coil balance each other out and voltage output is unchanged.
[src:voltage-references/shunt-regulator] Rotating the coil in one direction or the other away from the center position will increase or decrease voltage in the secondary movable coil.
[src:voltage-references/shunt-regulator] This type of regulator can be automated via a servo control mechanism to advance the movable coil position in order to provide voltage increase or decrease.
[src:voltage-references/shunt-regulator] A braking mechanism or high-ratio gearing is used to hold the rotating coil in place against the powerful magnetic forces acting on the moving coil.
[src:voltage-references/shunt-regulator] Electromechanical regulators called *voltage stabilizers* or *tap-changers*, have also been used to regulate the voltage on AC power distribution lines.
[src:voltage-references/shunt-regulator] These regulators operate by using a servomechanism to select the appropriate tap on an autotransformer with multiple taps, or by moving the wiper on a continuously variable auto transfomer.
[src:voltage-references/shunt-regulator] If the output voltage is not in the acceptable range, the servomechanism switches the tap, changing the turns ratio of the transformer, to move the secondary voltage into the acceptable region.
[src:voltage-references/shunt-regulator] The controls provide a dead band wherein the controller will not act, preventing the controller from constantly adjusting the voltage ("hunting") as it varies by an acceptably small amount.
[src:voltage-references/shunt-regulator] The **ferroresonant transformer**, **ferroresonant regulator** or **constant-voltage transformer** is a type of saturating transformer used as a voltage regulator.
[src:voltage-references/shunt-regulator] These transformers use a tank circuit composed of a high-voltage resonant winding and a capacitor to produce a nearly constant average output voltage with a varying input current or varying load.
[src:voltage-references/shunt-regulator] The circuit has a primary on one side of a magnet shunt and the tuned circuit coil and secondary on the other side.
[src:voltage-references/shunt-regulator] Voltage regulation results from magnetic saturation in the portion of the core associated with the resonant winding and secondary.
[src:voltage-references/shunt-regulator] The ferroresonant approach is attractive due to its lack of active components, relying on the square-loop magnetic characteristics of the core operating in saturation to absorb variations in average input voltage.
[src:voltage-references/shunt-regulator] Saturating transformers provide a simple rugged method to stabilize an AC power supply.
[src:voltage-references/shunt-regulator] Older designs produced outputs with significant harmonic content.
[src:voltage-references/shunt-regulator] Modern designs improve waveform quality, but the output is not an ideal sine wave.
[src:voltage-references/shunt-regulator] The ferroresonant action is a flux limiter rather than a voltage regulator, but with a fixed supply frequency it can maintain an almost constant average output voltage even as the input voltage varies widely.
[src:voltage-references/shunt-regulator] The ferroresonant transformers, which are also known as *constant-voltage transformers* (CVTs) or "ferros", are also good surge suppressors, as they provide high isolation and inherent short-circuit protection.
[src:voltage-references/shunt-regulator] A ferroresonant transformer can operate with an input voltage range ±40% or more of the nominal voltage.
[src:voltage-references/shunt-regulator] Output power factor remains in the range of 0.96 or higher from half to full load.
[src:voltage-references/shunt-regulator] Because it regenerates an output voltage waveform, output distortion, which is typically less than 4%, is independent of any input voltage distortion, including notching.
[src:voltage-references/shunt-regulator] Efficiency at full load is typically in the range of 89% to 93%.
[src:voltage-references/shunt-regulator] However, at low loads, efficiency can drop below 60%.
[src:voltage-references/shunt-regulator] The current-limiting capability also becomes a handicap when a CVT is used in an application with moderate to high inrush current, like motors, transformers or magnets.
[src:voltage-references/shunt-regulator] In this case, the CVT has to be sized to accommodate the peak current, thus forcing it to run at low loads and poor efficiency.
[src:voltage-references/shunt-regulator] Minimum maintenance is required, as transformers and capacitors can be very reliable.
[src:voltage-references/shunt-regulator] Some units have included redundant capacitors to allow several capacitors to fail between inspections without any noticeable effect on the device's performance.
[src:voltage-references/shunt-regulator] Output voltage varies about 1.2% for every 1% change in supply frequency.
[src:voltage-references/shunt-regulator] For example, a 2 Hz change in generator frequency, which is very large, results in an output voltage change of only 4%, which has little effect for most loads.
[src:voltage-references/shunt-regulator] It accepts 100% single-phase switch-mode power-supply loading without any requirement for derating, including all neutral components.
[src:voltage-references/shunt-regulator] Input current distortion remains less than 8% THD even when supplying nonlinear loads with more than 100% current THD.
[src:voltage-references/shunt-regulator] Drawbacks of CVTs are their larger size, audible humming sound, and the high heat generation caused by saturation.
[src:voltage-references/shunt-regulator] Some ferroresonant transformer have active control.
[src:voltage-references/shunt-regulator] Voltage regulators or stabilizers are used to compensate for voltage fluctuations in mains power.
[src:voltage-references/shunt-regulator] Large regulators may be permanently installed on distribution lines.
[src:voltage-references/shunt-regulator] Small portable regulators may be plugged in between sensitive equipment and a wall outlet.
[src:voltage-references/shunt-regulator] Automatic voltage regulators on generator sets to maintain a constant voltage for changes in load.
[src:voltage-references/shunt-regulator] The voltage regulator compensates for the change in load.
[src:voltage-references/shunt-regulator] Power distribution voltage regulators normally operate on a range of voltages, for example 150–240 V or 90–280 V.
[src:voltage-references/shunt-regulator] Many simple DC power supplies regulate the voltage using either series or shunt regulators, but most apply a voltage reference using a *shunt regulator* such as a Zener diode, avalanche breakdown diode, or voltage regulator tube.
[src:voltage-references/shunt-regulator] The power supply is designed to only supply a maximum amount of current that is within the safe operating capability of the shunt regulating device.
[src:voltage-references/shunt-regulator] If the stabilizer must provide more power, the shunt output is only used to provide the standard voltage reference for the electronic device, known as the voltage stabilizer.
[src:voltage-references/shunt-regulator] The voltage stabilizer is the electronic device, able to deliver much larger currents on demand.
[src:voltage-references/shunt-regulator] Active regulators employ at least one active (amplifying) component such as a transistor or operational amplifier.
[src:voltage-references/shunt-regulator] Shunt regulators are often (but not always) passive and simple, but always inefficient because they (essentially) dump the excess current which is not available to the load.
[src:voltage-references/shunt-regulator] When more power must be supplied, more sophisticated circuits are used.
[src:voltage-references/shunt-regulator] In the past, one or more vacuum tubes were commonly used as the variable resistance.
[src:voltage-references/shunt-regulator] Modern designs like Shakti Servo use one or more transistors instead, perhaps within an integrated circuit.
[src:voltage-references/shunt-regulator] Linear designs have the advantage of very "clean" output with little noise introduced into their DC output, but are most often much less efficient and unable to step-up or invert the input voltage like switched supplies.
[src:voltage-references/shunt-regulator] All linear regulators require a higher input than the output.
[src:voltage-references/shunt-regulator] If the input voltage approaches the desired output voltage, the regulator will "drop out".
[src:voltage-references/shunt-regulator] The input to output voltage differential at which this occurs is known as the regulator's drop-out voltage.
[src:voltage-references/shunt-regulator] Low-dropout regulators (LDOs) allow an input voltage that can be much lower (i.e., they waste less energy than conventional linear regulators).
[src:voltage-references/shunt-regulator] Entire linear regulators are available as integrated circuits.
[src:voltage-references/shunt-regulator] These chips come in either fixed or adjustable voltage types.
[src:voltage-references/shunt-regulator] A switching regulator works similar to an appliance charger.
[src:voltage-references/shunt-regulator] When battery charge is low, a charger is plugged in and energy is transferred to the battery.
[src:voltage-references/shunt-regulator] When charge is high, the charger disables itself, or is unplugged.
[src:voltage-references/shunt-regulator] A switching regulator nominally cycles hundreds to tens of thousands times per second automatically.
[src:voltage-references/shunt-regulator] The duty cycle is controlled by a similar feedback mechanism as in a linear regulator.
[src:voltage-references/shunt-regulator] Because the series element is either fully conducting, or switched off, it dissipates almost no power; this is what gives the switching design its efficiency.
[src:voltage-references/shunt-regulator] Switching regulators are also able to generate output voltages which are higher than the input, or of opposite polarity—something not possible with a linear design.
[src:voltage-references/shunt-regulator] In switched regulators, the pass transistor is used as a "controlled switch" and is operated at either cutoff or saturated state.
[src:voltage-references/shunt-regulator] Hence the power transmitted across the pass device is in discrete pulses rather than a steady current flow.
[src:voltage-references/shunt-regulator] Greater efficiency is achieved since the pass device is operated as a low-impedance switch.
[src:voltage-references/shunt-regulator] When the pass device is at cutoff, there is no current and it dissipates no power.
[src:voltage-references/shunt-regulator] Again when the pass device is in saturation, a negligible voltage drop appears across it and thus dissipates only a small amount of average power, providing maximum current to the load.
[src:voltage-references/shunt-regulator] In either case, the power wasted in the pass device is very little and almost all the power is transmitted to the load.
[src:voltage-references/shunt-regulator] Thus the efficiency of a switched-mode power supply is remarkably high – in the range of 70–90%.
[src:voltage-references/shunt-regulator] Switched mode regulators rely on pulse-width modulation to control the average value of the output voltage.
[src:voltage-references/shunt-regulator] The average value of a repetitive-pulse waveform depends on the area under the waveform.
[src:voltage-references/shunt-regulator] When the duty cycle is varied, the average voltage changes proportionally.
[src:voltage-references/shunt-regulator] Like linear regulators, nearly complete switching regulators are also available as integrated circuits (e.g.
[src:voltage-references/shunt-regulator] Unlike linear regulators, these usually require an inductor for step-up or capacitor for step-down, that acts as the energy storage element.
[src:voltage-references/shunt-regulator] The IC regulators combine the reference voltage source, error op-amp, and pass transistor with short-circuit current limiting and thermal-overload protection.
[src:voltage-references/shunt-regulator] Switching regulators are more prone to input noise, output noise, and instability than linear regulators.
[src:voltage-references/shunt-regulator] However, they provide much better power efficiency than linear regulators.
[src:voltage-references/shunt-regulator] Regulators powered from AC power circuits can use silicon controlled rectifiers (SCRs) as the series device.
[src:voltage-references/shunt-regulator] Whenever the output voltage is below the desired value, the SCR is triggered, allowing electricity to flow into the load until the AC mains voltage passes through zero (ending the half cycle).
[src:voltage-references/shunt-regulator] SCR regulators have the advantages of being both very efficient and very simple, but because they can not terminate an ongoing half cycle of conduction, they are not capable of very accurate voltage regulation in response to rapidly changing loads.
[src:voltage-references/shunt-regulator] An alternative is the SCR shunt regulator which uses the regulator output as a trigger.
[src:voltage-references/shunt-regulator] Both series and shunt designs are noisy, but powerful, as the device has a low on resistance.
[src:voltage-references/shunt-regulator] Many power supplies use more than one regulating method in series.
[src:voltage-references/shunt-regulator] For example, the output from a switching regulator can be further regulated by a linear regulator.
[src:voltage-references/shunt-regulator] The switching regulator accepts a wide range of input voltages and efficiently generates a (somewhat noisy) voltage slightly above the ultimately desired output.
[src:voltage-references/shunt-regulator] That is followed by a linear regulator that generates exactly the desired voltage and eliminates nearly all the noise generated by the switching regulator.
[src:voltage-references/shunt-regulator] Other designs may use an SCR regulator as the "pre-regulator", followed by another type of regulator.
[src:voltage-references/shunt-regulator] An efficient way of creating a variable-voltage, accurate output power supply is to combine a multi-tapped transformer with an adjustable linear post-regulator.
[src:voltage-references/shunt-regulator] A simple transistor regulator will provide a relatively constant output voltage *U*out for changes in the voltage *U*in of the power source and for changes in load *R*L, provided that *U*in exceeds *U*out by a sufficient margin and that the power handling capacity of the transistor is not exceeded.
[src:voltage-references/shunt-regulator] The output voltage of the stabilizer is equal to the Zener diode voltage minus the base–emitter voltage of the transistor, *U*Z − *U*BE, where *U*BE is usually about 0.7 V for a silicon transistor, depending on the load current.
[src:voltage-references/shunt-regulator] In this case, the operational amplifier drives the transistor with more current if the voltage at its inverting input drops below the output of the voltage reference at the non-inverting input.
[src:voltage-references/shunt-regulator] Using the voltage divider (R1, R2 and R3) allows choice of the arbitrary output voltage between Uz and Uin.
[src:voltage-references/shunt-regulator] The output voltage can only be held constant within specified limits.
[src:voltage-references/voltage-reference] A **voltage reference** is an electronic device that ideally produces a fixed (constant) voltage irrespective of the loading on the device, power supply variations, temperature changes, and the passage of time.
[src:voltage-references/voltage-reference] Voltage references are used in power supplies, analog-to-digital converters, digital-to-analog converters, and other measurement and control systems.
[src:voltage-references/voltage-reference] Voltage references vary widely in performance; a regulator for a computer power supply may only hold its value to within a few percent of the nominal value, whereas laboratory voltage standards have precisions and stability measured in parts per million.
[src:voltage-references/voltage-reference] The earliest voltage references or standards were wet chemical cells such as the Clark cell and Weston cell, which are still used in some laboratory and calibration applications.
[src:voltage-references/voltage-reference] Laboratory-grade Zener diode secondary solid-state voltage standards used in metrology can be constructed with a drift of about 1 part per million per year.
[src:voltage-references/voltage-reference] The value of the "conventional" volt is now maintained by superconductive integrated circuits using the Josephson effect to get a voltage to an accuracy of 1 parts per billion or better, the Josephson voltage standard.
[src:voltage-references/voltage-reference] The paper titled, "Possible new effects in superconductive tunnelling", was published by Brian David Josephson in 1962 and earned Josephson the Nobel Prize in Physics in 1973.
[src:voltage-references/voltage-reference] Formerly, mercury batteries were much used as convenient voltage references especially in portable instruments such as photographic light meters; mercury batteries had a very stable discharge voltage over their useful life.
[src:voltage-references/voltage-reference] Any semiconductor diode has an exponential current–voltage characteristic that can be viewed as having a "knee" voltage, sometimes used as an imprecise voltage reference.
[src:voltage-references/voltage-reference] Datasheets may list a forward voltage drop at a specified "on" current.
[src:voltage-references/voltage-reference] This voltage is around 0.3 V for germanium diodes, around 0.6 V to 0.7 V for silicon diodes, and from 1.6 V (red) to 4 V (violet) for visible light emitting diodes.
[src:voltage-references/voltage-reference] These devices have a strong temperature dependence, which may make them useful for temperature measurement or for compensating bias in analog circuits.
[src:voltage-references/voltage-reference] Zener diodes are also frequently used to provide a reference voltage of moderate stability and accuracy, useful for many electronic devices.
[src:voltage-references/voltage-reference] An avalanche diode displays a similar stable voltage over a range of current.
[src:voltage-references/voltage-reference] The most common voltage reference circuit used in integrated circuits is the bandgap voltage reference.
[src:voltage-references/voltage-reference] A bandgap-based reference (commonly just called a 'bandgap') uses analog circuits to add a multiple of the voltage difference between two bipolar junctions biased at different current densities to the voltage developed across a diode.
[src:voltage-references/voltage-reference] The diode voltage has a negative temperature coefficient (i.e. it decreases with increasing temperature), and the junction voltage difference has a positive temperature coefficient.
[src:voltage-references/voltage-reference] When added in the proportion required to make these coefficients cancel out, the resultant constant value is a voltage equal to the bandgap voltage of the semiconductor.
[src:voltage-references/voltage-reference] In silicon, this is approximately 1.25 V.
[src:voltage-references/voltage-reference] Buried-Zener references can provide even lower noise levels, but require higher operating voltages that are not available in many battery-operated devices.
[src:voltage-references/voltage-reference] Gas filled tubes and neon lamps have also been used as voltage references, primarily in tube-based equipment, as the voltage needed to sustain the gas discharge is comparatively constant.
[src:voltage-references/voltage-reference] For example, the popular RCA 991 "voltage regulator tube" is an NE-16 neon lamp, which fires at 87 volts and then holds 48 to 67 volts across the discharge path.
[src:voltage-references/zener-diode] A **Zener diode** is a type of diode designed to exploit the Zener effect to affect electric current to flow against the normal direction from anode to cathode, when the voltage across its terminals exceeds a certain characteristic threshold, the *Zener voltage*.
[src:voltage-references/zener-diode] Zener diodes are manufactured with a variety of Zener voltages, including variable devices.
[src:voltage-references/zener-diode] Some types have an abrupt, heavily doped p–n junction with a low Zener voltage, in which case the reverse conduction occurs due to electron quantum tunnelling in the short distance between p and n regions.
[src:voltage-references/zener-diode] Diodes with a higher Zener voltage have more lightly doped junctions, causing their mode of operation to involve avalanche breakdown.
[src:voltage-references/zener-diode] Both breakdown types are present in Zener diodes with the Zener effect predominating at lower voltages and avalanche breakdown at higher voltages.
[src:voltage-references/zener-diode] Zener diodes are used to generate low-power stabilized supply rails from higher voltages and to provide reference voltages for circuits, especially stabilized power supplies.
[src:voltage-references/zener-diode] They are also used to protect circuits from overvoltage, especially electrostatic discharge.
[src:voltage-references/zener-diode] The device is named after American physicist Clarence Zener, who first described the Zener effect in 1934 in his primarily theoretical studies of the breakdown of electrical insulator properties.
[src:voltage-references/zener-diode] Later, his work led to the Bell Labs implementation of the effect in the form of an electronic device.
[src:voltage-references/zener-diode] A conventional solid-state diode allows significant current if it is reverse biased above its reverse-breakdown voltage.
[src:voltage-references/zener-diode] When the reverse-bias breakdown voltage is exceeded, a conventional diode will conduct a high current due to avalanche breakdown.
[src:voltage-references/zener-diode] Unless this current is limited by external circuits, the diode may be permanently damaged due to overheating at the small (localized) areas of the semiconductor junction where avalanche breakdown conduction is occurring.
[src:voltage-references/zener-diode] A Zener diode exhibits almost the same properties, except the device is specially designed so as to have a reduced breakdown voltage, the *Zener voltage*.
[src:voltage-references/zener-diode] By contrast with the conventional device, a reverse-biased Zener diode exhibits a controlled breakdown and allows the current to keep the voltage across the Zener diode close to the Zener breakdown voltage.
[src:voltage-references/zener-diode] For example, a diode with a Zener breakdown voltage of 3.2 V exhibits a voltage drop of very nearly 3.2 V across a wide range of reverse currents.
[src:voltage-references/zener-diode] The Zener diode is therefore well suited for applications such as the generation of a reference voltage (e.g. for an amplifier stage), or as a voltage stabilizer for low-current applications.
[src:voltage-references/zener-diode] Another mechanism that produces a similar effect is the avalanche effect as in the avalanche diode.
[src:voltage-references/zener-diode] The two types of diode are in fact constructed in similar ways and both effects are present in diodes of this type.
[src:voltage-references/zener-diode] In silicon diodes up to about 5.6 volts, the Zener effect is the predominant effect and shows a marked negative temperature coefficient.
[src:voltage-references/zener-diode] Above 5.6 volts, the avalanche effect dominates and exhibits a positive temperature coefficient.
[src:voltage-references/zener-diode] In a 5.6 V diode, the two effects occur together, and their temperature coefficients nearly cancel each other out, thus the 5.6 V diode is useful in temperature-critical applications.
[src:voltage-references/zener-diode] The forward-biased diode has a temperature coefficient of −2 mV/°C, causing the TCs to cancel out for a near-zero net temperature coefficient.
[src:voltage-references/zener-diode] Modern designs have produced devices with voltages lower than 5.6 V with negligible temperature coefficients,.
[src:voltage-references/zener-diode] Higher-voltage devices have temperature coefficients that are approximately proportional to the amount by which the breakdown voltage exceeds 5 V.
[src:voltage-references/zener-diode] Thus a 75 V diode has about ten times the coefficient of a 12 V diode.
[src:voltage-references/zener-diode] Zener and avalanche diodes, regardless of breakdown voltage, are usually marketed under the umbrella term of "Zener diode".
[src:voltage-references/zener-diode] Under 5.6 V, where the Zener effect dominates, the IV curve near breakdown is much more rounded, which calls for more care in choosing its biasing conditions.
[src:voltage-references/zener-diode] The IV curve for Zeners above 5.6 V (being dominated by avalanche), is much more precise at breakdown.
[src:voltage-references/zener-diode] The Zener diode's operation depends on the heavy doping of its p–n junction.
[src:voltage-references/zener-diode] At the atomic scale, this tunneling corresponds to the transport of valence-band electrons into the empty conduction-band states, as a result of the reduced barrier between these bands and high electric fields that are induced due to the high levels of doping on both sides.
[src:voltage-references/zener-diode] The breakdown voltage can be controlled quite accurately by the doping process.
[src:voltage-references/zener-diode] Adding impurities, or doping, changes the behaviour of the semiconductor material in the diode.
[src:voltage-references/zener-diode] In the case of Zener diodes, this heavy doping creates a situation where the diode can operate in the breakdown region.
[src:voltage-references/zener-diode] While tolerances within 0.07% are available, commonly available tolerances are 5% and 10%.
[src:voltage-references/zener-diode] Breakdown voltage for commonly available Zener diodes can vary from 1.2 V to 200 V.
[src:voltage-references/zener-diode] For diodes that are lightly doped, the breakdown is dominated by the avalanche effect rather than the Zener effect.
[src:voltage-references/zener-diode] Consequently, the breakdown voltage is higher (over 5.6 V) for these devices.
[src:voltage-references/zener-diode] The emitter–base junction of a bipolar NPN transistor behaves as a Zener diode, with breakdown voltage at about 6.8 V for common bipolar processes and about 10 V for lightly doped base regions in BiCMOS processes.
[src:voltage-references/zener-diode] Older processes with poor control of doping characteristics had the variation of Zener voltage up to ±1 V, newer processes using ion implantation can achieve no more than ±0.25 V.
[src:voltage-references/zener-diode] The NPN transistor structure can be employed as a *surface Zener diode*, with collector and emitter connected together as its cathode and base region as anode.
[src:voltage-references/zener-diode] In this approach the base doping profile usually narrows towards the surface, creating a region with intensified electric field where the avalanche breakdown occurs.
[src:voltage-references/zener-diode] Hot carriers produced by acceleration in the intense field can inject into the oxide layer above the junction and become trapped there.
[src:voltage-references/zener-diode] The accumulation of trapped charges can then cause 'Zener walkout', a corresponding change of the Zener voltage of the junction.
[src:voltage-references/zener-diode] The same effect can be achieved by radiation damage.
[src:voltage-references/zener-diode] The emitter–base Zener diodes can handle only low currents as the energy is dissipated in the base depletion region which is very small.
[src:voltage-references/zener-diode] Higher amounts of dissipated energy (higher current for longer time, or a short very high current spike) causes thermal damage to the junction and/or its contacts.
[src:voltage-references/zener-diode] Partial damage of the junction can shift its Zener voltage.
[src:voltage-references/zener-diode] Total destruction of the Zener junction by overheating it and causing migration of metallization across the junction ("spiking") can be used intentionally as a 'Zener zap' antifuse.
[src:voltage-references/zener-diode] A subsurface Zener diode, also called a *buried Zener*, is a device similar to the surface Zener, but the doping and design is such that the avalanche region is located deeper in the structure, typically several micrometers below the oxide.
[src:voltage-references/zener-diode] Hot carriers then lose energy by collisions with the semiconductor lattice before reaching the oxide layer and cannot be trapped there.
[src:voltage-references/zener-diode] The Zener walkout phenomenon therefore does not occur here, and the buried Zeners have stable voltage over their entire lifetime.
[src:voltage-references/zener-diode] Most buried Zeners have breakdown voltage of 5–7 volts.
[src:voltage-references/zener-diode] Several different junction structures are used.
[src:voltage-references/zener-diode] Zener diodes are widely used as voltage references and as shunt regulators to regulate the voltage across small circuits.
[src:voltage-references/zener-diode] When connected in parallel with a variable voltage source so that it is reverse biased, a Zener diode conducts when the voltage reaches the diode's reverse breakdown voltage.
[src:voltage-references/zener-diode] From that point on, the low impedance of the diode keeps the voltage across the diode at that value.
[src:voltage-references/zener-diode] In this circuit, a typical voltage reference or regulator, an input voltage, *U*in (with + on the top), is regulated down to a stable output voltage *U*out.
[src:voltage-references/zener-diode] The breakdown voltage of diode D is stable over a wide current range and holds *U*out approximately constant even though the input voltage may fluctuate over a wide range.
[src:voltage-references/zener-diode] Because of the low impedance of the diode when operated like this, resistor *R* is used to limit current through the circuit.
[src:voltage-references/zener-diode] *R* must be large enough that the current through D does not destroy the device.
[src:voltage-references/zener-diode] If the current through D is *I*D, its breakdown voltage *V*B and its maximum power dissipation *P*max correlate as such: $I_{D}V_{B}<P_{\text{max}}$ .
[src:voltage-references/zener-diode] A load may be placed across the diode in this reference circuit, and as long as the Zener stays in reverse breakdown, the diode provides a stable voltage source to the load.
[src:voltage-references/zener-diode] Zener diodes in this configuration are often used as stable references for more advanced voltage regulator circuits.
[src:voltage-references/zener-diode] These devices are also encountered, typically in series with a base–emitter junction, in transistor stages where selective choice of a device centered on the avalanche or Zener point can be used to introduce compensating temperature co-efficient balancing of the transistor p–n junction.
[src:voltage-references/zener-diode] An example of this kind of use would be a DC error amplifier used in a regulated power supply circuit feedback loop system.
[src:voltage-references/zener-diode] Zener diodes are also used in surge protectors to limit transient voltage spikes.
[src:voltage-references/zener-diode] Another application of the Zener diode is using its avalanche breakdown noise (see noise generator § Zener diode), which for instance can be used for dithering in an analog-to-digital converter when at a rms level equivalent to 1⁄3 to 1 lsb or to create a random number generator.
[src:voltage-references/zener-diode] Two Zener diodes facing each other in series clip both halves of an input signal.
[src:voltage-references/zener-diode] Waveform clippers can be used not only to reshape a signal, but also to prevent voltage spikes from affecting circuits that are connected to the power supply.
[src:voltage-references/zener-diode] A Zener diode can be applied to a circuit with a resistor to act as a voltage shifter.
[src:voltage-references/zener-diode] This circuit lowers the output voltage by a quantity that is equal to the Zener diode's breakdown voltage.
[src:voltage-references/zener-diode] A Zener diode can be applied in a voltage regulator circuit to regulate the voltage applied to a load, such as in a linear regulator.
